(41, 16, 1, 40, 28, 1, 10, 'Mary Magdalene', 'Women at the Tomb', 'Both passages emphasize the presence of Mary Magdalene and other women visiting the tomb after the Sabbath. They highlight the women''s role in discovering the resurrection of Jesus, linking their actions in both accounts.', 'parallel', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 16, 1, 43, 20, 1, 10, 'Mary Magdalene', 'Mary Magdalene''s Role', 'Both passages emphasize Mary Magdalene''s presence at the tomb. In Mark, she prepares spices to anoint Jesus, while in John, she discovers the stone rolled away and informs the disciples.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 16, 1, 41, 15, 40, 40, NULL, 'Women at the Crucifixion and Resurrection', 'Both passages emphasize the presence of Mary Magdalene and Salome. This connection highlights their role in witnessing Jesus'' death and their actions following the Sabbath.', 'parallel', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 16, 1, 14, 16, 14, 14, 'sweet spices', 'Use of Spices in Burial', 'Both passages emphasize the use of sweet spices in burial practices. In Mark, the women bring spices to anoint Jesus, while in 2 Chronicles, spices are mentioned in the context of a royal burial.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 16, 1, 41, 14, 3, 3, 'anoint him', 'Anointing of Jesus', 'Both passages emphasize the act of anointing Jesus. In Mark 14:3, a woman anoints Jesus with precious ointment, while in Mark 16:1, the women bring spices to anoint him after his burial.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 16, 1, 43, 19, 25, 25, 'Mary Magdalene', 'Women at the Crucifixion and Burial', 'Both passages emphasize the presence of women, specifically Mary Magdalene, in significant moments surrounding Jesus'' death and burial. This connection highlights their roles in mourning and honoring Jesus.', 'parallel', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 16, 2, 43, 20, 1, 1, 'the first day of the week', 'Resurrection Morning Accounts', 'Both passages emphasize the timing of the visit to the sepulchre on the first day of the week. Mark notes the visit occurred at sunrise, while John specifies it was early and still dark, highlighting the significance of this moment.', 'parallel', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 16, 2, 40, 28, 1, 1, 'first day of the week', 'Resurrection Morning Accounts', 'Both passages emphasize the timing of the visit to the sepulchre, specifically noting it occurs at dawn on the first day of the week. This connection highlights the significance of the resurrection event occurring early in the morning.', 'parallel', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 16, 2, 42, 24, 1, 1, NULL, 'Resurrection Morning Accounts', 'Both passages emphasize the timing of the visit to the sepulchre on the first day of the week, very early in the morning. This connection highlights the shared detail of the women coming to the tomb at sunrise.', 'parallel', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 16, 3, 41, 15, 46, 47, 'roll us away the stone', 'Stone at the Sepulchre', 'Both passages emphasize the stone at the sepulchre. In Mark 15:46-47, the stone is rolled to the door, while in Mark 16:3, the women express concern about who will roll it away.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 16, 3, 40, 27, 60, 66, 'Who shall roll us away the stone', 'Stone at the Sepulchre', 'Both passages emphasize the stone at the sepulchre, highlighting the concern of the women in Mark about who would roll it away. Matthew describes the stone being rolled to secure the tomb, indicating its significance in the resurrection narrative.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 16, 4, 40, 28, 2, 4, 'the stone was rolled away', 'Resurrection Stone Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the stone being rolled away, indicating the event of the resurrection. Mark notes the stone''s great size, while Matthew describes the angel''s role in moving it.', 'parallel', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 16, 4, 42, 24, 2, 2, 'the stone was rolled away', 'Connection of the Rolled Stone', 'Both passages emphasize the stone being rolled away from the tomb, highlighting a significant event in the resurrection narrative. This shared detail underscores the miraculous nature of the resurrection.', 'parallel', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 16, 4, 43, 20, 1, 1, 'the stone was rolled away', 'Resurrection Stone Removal', 'Both passages emphasize the stone being rolled away from the sepulchre, highlighting the miraculous event of the resurrection. The descriptions in Mark and John serve to confirm the reality of the empty tomb.', 'parallel', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 16, 5, 43, 20, 11, 12, 'clothed in a long white garment', 'Angels at the Tomb', 'Both passages emphasize the presence of angels at the sepulchre. Mark mentions a young man in white, while John describes two angels in white, highlighting the divine revelation at Jesus'' burial site.', 'parallel', 0.37, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 16, 5, 40, 28, 3, 3, 'clothed in a long white garment', 'Descriptions of the Angelic Figure', 'Both passages emphasize the appearance of the angelic figure at the tomb. Mark describes the figure as ''clothed in a long white garment,'' while Matthew highlights the brightness of the figure''s appearance, stating ''raiment white as snow.''', 'parallel', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 16, 5, 42, 24, 3, 5, 'clothed in a long white garment', 'Angelic Presence at the Tomb', 'Both passages emphasize the presence of heavenly beings at the tomb. In Mark, a young man in white is seen, while Luke describes two men in shining garments, highlighting the divine message delivered to the women.', 'parallel', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 16, 5, 42, 1, 29, 30, NULL, 'Fear and Divine Presence', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of fear in the presence of a divine messenger. In Mark, the women are ''affrighted'' by the young man, while in Luke, Mary is ''troubled'' by the angel''s greeting.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 16, 5, 41, 6, 49, 50, NULL, 'Fear and Comfort in Crisis', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of fear and the subsequent reassurance provided by a divine figure. In Mark 16:5, the women are ''affrighted'' by the young man, while in Mark 6:50, the disciples are ''troubled'' until Jesus comforts them with ''be not afraid.''', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 16, 5, 41, 9, 15, 15, 'affrighted', 'Fear and Amazement in Encounters', 'Both passages emphasize a strong reaction of fear and amazement in the presence of the divine. In Mark 16:5, the women are ''affrighted'' by the young man, while in Mark 9:15, the people are ''greatly amazed'' upon seeing Jesus.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 16, 5, 27, 8, 17, 17, 'they were affrighted', 'Fear and Divine Presence', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of fear in the presence of a divine being. In Mark, the women are ''affrighted'' by the young man, while in Daniel, the prophet falls in fear before the angelic figure.', 'theme', 0.307, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 16, 6, 66, 1, 17, 18, 'Be not affrighted', 'Resurrection and Fear Not', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of overcoming fear through the proclamation of Jesus'' resurrection. In Mark, the angel reassures the women with ''Be not affrighted,'' while in Revelation, Jesus comforts John with ''Fear not.''', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 16, 6, 42, 24, 46, 46, 'he is risen; he is not here', 'Resurrection of Christ', 'Both passages emphasize the resurrection of Jesus. Mark 16:6 declares that Jesus is risen, while Luke 24:46 states that Christ must rise from the dead, highlighting the necessity of his resurrection.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 16, 6, 46, 15, 3, 7, 'he is risen', 'Resurrection of Jesus', 'Both passages emphasize the resurrection of Jesus. Mark 16:6 declares that ''he is risen,'' while 1 Corinthians 15:4 states that ''he rose again the third day.'' This connection highlights the centrality of the resurrection in early Christian proclamation.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
